# Digital Signature Flow (RETMS)

Date: 2026-04-18

## Overview

This document describes the end-to-end digital signature (DSC) flow used by RETMS. It covers the interactions between the user, frontend (Angular), local DSC agent, backend (RETMS API), storage (MinIO) and database, including API endpoints, request/response shapes, and verification steps.

## Components

- Frontend — Angular app (`DigitalSignatureService`) that orchestrates signing.
- Local DSC Agent — Runs on the user's machine; performs private-key signing with USB token and returns PKCS#7.
- Backend — RETMS API (`digital-signature` module) that issues signing tokens, verifies signatures, logs audits, and stores signed PDFs.
- Storage — MinIO (object storage) for storing PDFs.
- Database — Postgres tables: `notices`, `dsc_audit_log`, `dsc_certificates`.

## High-level sequence

1. User triggers "Sign" in UI.
2. Frontend checks local DSC agent health (`GET /health`).
3. Frontend requests a signing token from backend (`POST /digital-signature/request-sign`).
4. Backend fetches or generates the PDF, computes `fileHash`, and returns a short-lived JWT + metadata.
5. Frontend downloads the PDF (`GET /digital-signature/download-pdf/:documentId`).
6. Frontend sends PDF + PIN + JWT to the local DSC agent (`POST /sign`).
7. Agent verifies the JWT/public key, validates hash, produces a signed PDF (PKCS#7), and responds with the signed PDF blob and `X-PKCS7-Signature` header.
8. Frontend converts the signed PDF blob to base64 and posts it to backend (`POST /digital-signature/submit-signed`) with the original JWT and optional PKCS#7 hex.
9. Backend verifies the JWT, recomputes/extracts hash, verifies PKCS#7, validates certificate/chain/revocation, performs TSA checks, logs an audit, signs a verification proof, stores the signed PDF in object storage, and updates the notice status to `signed`.

